Spectre




James Bond fans need not fear Spectre of product placement









Yes, there are brands to be seen in the latest Bond film but, unlike some past 007 outings, retail showboating does not trip up the action






















































Cheers: Léa Seydoux and Daniel Craig in Spectre.
Photograph: Allstar/United Artists










Spectre




James Bond fans need not fear Spectre of product placement









Yes, there are brands to be seen in the latest Bond film but, unlike some past 007 outings, retail showboating does not trip up the action












Share on Facebook









Share on Twitter









Share via Email
















View more sharing options




Share on LinkedIn









Share on Pinterest









Share on Google+









Share on WhatsApp









Share on Messenger









Close

















Henry Barnes







@HenryHBarnes




Thursday 22 October 2015 07.13 EDT


Last modified on Monday 5 June 2017 20.28 EDT






Spectre, the longest, most expensive Bond yet, wouldn’t have been made without product placement. There is always a hoo-ha about this sort of thing. The sanctity of Ian Fleming’s character suddenly becomes paramount. His watch is wrong! His car is wrong! He’s also stopped hitting women. He might, one day, be black. 




Spectre review: James Bond is back, stylish, camp and sexily pro-Snowden






 


Read more






Good news for those peeved by 007 drinking a beer in Skyfall, Spectre is subtle in its product placement. Three brands are mentioned by name – two car manufacturers and a gunmaker – and only one is an official sponsor. Bond drinks a vodka martini, but doesn’t ask for it by brand. He doles out champagne, but the label’s left hidden. The close-ups we get of logos are of a restaurant where M (Ralph Fiennes) is eating alone and a scene where he is reading in a newspaper about an escapade in Mexico that’s gone awry. That’s a shot of a copy of the Guardian, on to which M slaps a copy of the Times. Advertising is at play; still, we are a long way from the grand-scale product flog of “Buy Another Day”. 











 


  Facebook 
 


  Twitter 
 


  Pinterest 





  The film team review Spectre


Daniel Craig, not shy about advertising his feelings on the character and the franchise, has described product placement in the Bond films as “a fact of life”. But, increasingly sponsorship in Bond – at least in the Craig era – has become a fact of the real world, while the fiction is left alone. The use of the actors in selling stuff around the films is brazen and often crass, but it’s allowed Sam Mendes and his writing team to avoid too much out-and-out endorsement in Spectre. It’s a fair trade for fans: let Naomie Harris race around the Southbank in pursuit of a mobile phone on the telly ads, so that the film stays relatively unsullied.
The real world also offers moments of real people rejecting the script. Both Mendes and Craig expressed doubts about the quality of the studio’s choice of mobile phone for the character in Spectre. There’s something delightfully contradictory (and not very suave) about Daniel Craig being paid millions to clotheshorse all this swag, while bitching about it in private. Very off-brand Daniel. 





 


  Facebook 
 


  Twitter 
 


  Pinterest 


Bond – moneyed, stylish, aspirational – has always been a potent brand for advertisers to associate themselves with. But, with Spectre, it’s almost as if the brand has branched into two: the Bond of the film and the Bond that can be used to sell. It’s a canny strategy, allowing Craig, Mendes and producer Barbara Broccoli to bolster both their artistic credibility and their product placement fees. 
Spectre is cornier than Skyfall, less gripping than Casino Royale. The plot is baggy, the real-world concerns (surveillance and civil liberties) are as throwaway as ever. The film has its problems, but product placement isn’t one of them. 


